## What Each Dropped Index Category Covers and Why It's Redundant

### Cluster+Partition (10 indexes dropped)
`cluster_partition` is an occasional filter. When used, the query already has `cluster=?` which lets `jobs_cluster_starttime_duration` or `jobs_cluster_jobstate_duration_starttime` seek to the cluster, then the partition filter is applied as a cheap row-level check. Only one partition index is kept (#21) for the most common combination. At 20M rows with perhaps 5-20 partitions per cluster, the cluster index narrows results sufficiently.

### Cluster+Shared (8 indexes dropped)
`shared` filtering is rare (occasional). When applied, it is a cheap boolean-like filter on rows already narrowed by cluster. No dedicated indexes needed.

### Shared-prefixed (8 indexes dropped)
Same reasoning -- shared alone is never a leading filter in any significant query pattern.

### Duplicate sort indexes (10 single-filter+sort dropped)
Indexes like `(num_nodes, start_time)` and `(num_nodes, duration)` are only useful when `num_nodes` is the *only* filter and a sort is needed. In practice, queries nearly always have `cluster` and/or `job_state` as leading filters. The cluster-prefixed sort indexes (#13-17) handle these cases. For the rare unfiltered sort by num_nodes, SQLite will use `jobs_starttime` for the dominant start_time sort or do a bounded scan with LIMIT.

### Standalone duration (1 dropped)
`(duration)` alone is only useful for unfiltered sort-by-duration queries, which are extremely rare. `jobs_cluster_duration_starttime` handles the common cluster+sort-duration case.

### User sort variants (4 dropped: user+numnodes, user+numhwthreads, user+numacc, user+energy)
When a user filters by `hpc_user`, the result set is already small (one user's jobs). Sorting these few thousand rows in a temp B-tree is fast. Only `jobs_user_starttime_duration` is kept for the dominant sort.

### Project sort variants (4 dropped: same pattern)
Same reasoning as user. `jobs_project_starttime_duration` covers the dominant case.

### JobState sort variants (4 dropped: state+numnodes, state+numhwthreads, state+numacc, state+energy)
Job state has very low cardinality (6 values). State-only filters are uncommon; cluster+state is the norm and is handled by Group 2 indexes.

